  "text": "2.2.1. Tail-based approach. [CITATION_1] proposed an intuitive method for estimating the proportion of null hypotheses using p-value plots. The methodology is developed for the general mixture model (1). To illustrate how it works, we simulated n = 1000 observations from a simple two-point normal mixture F (x) = (1 − n)N (0, 1) + nN (2, 1). The proportion of non-null hypotheses is n = 0.2. The histogram of the p-values is shown in panel (a) of Figure 2 . Under the sparsity assumption, the majority of large pvalues should come from the null distribution. Let λ be a sufficiently large threshold, say λ = 0.5. Denote W (λ) = #{i : pi > λ}. Since the p-values to the right of the threshold roughly follow a uniform distribution, the expected counts covered by light grey bars can be approximated as E{W (λ)} ≈ n(1 − n)(1 − λ). Setting the expected and actual counts equal, we obtain an estimateˆ",
